<paragraph blockId="61.[136,1452,1274,1841]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
Thallus corticolous, pendulous or subpendulous, pale yellow, more or less rigid, dichotomously branched, 
<quantity box="[1339,1451,1274,1301]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" unit="cm" value="20.0" valueMax="25.0" valueMin="15.0">15–25 cm</quantity>
long. Branches solid, flattened, contorted, 
<quantity box="[612,705,1310,1337]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" unit="mm" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3–5 mm</quantity>
wide, with verruculose surface. Pseudocyphellae not seen. Soralia not seen. Cortical tissue paraplectenchymatous, 12–16 µm thick; chondroid tissue continuous; medullary layer dense, continuous. Pycnidia not seen. Apothecia abundant, lateral, non-spurred, discs flat to convex, 
<quantity box="[1212,1308,1382,1409]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" unit="mm" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3–5 mm</quantity>
in diameter, reddish brown; epithecium 8–10 µm thick; hymenium 44–46 µm thick; hypothecium 16–20 µm thick. Ascospores 1–septate, colorless, short-ellipsoid, 8–10 x 4–4.5 µm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="61.[136,1452,1274,1841]" box="[189,1101,1490,1517]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,315,1490,1516]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Chemistry</emphasis>
(
<collectionCode box="[330,387,1490,1516]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">TLC</collectionCode>
, 
<collectionCode box="[399,494,1490,1516]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">HPTLC</collectionCode>
): Divaricatic, boninic and 2ˊ– 
<emphasis box="[825,845,1491,1517]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
<collectionCode box="[825,845,1491,1517]" country="Norway" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:13093" name="Botanical Museum - University of Oslo" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" type="Herbarium">O</collectionCode>
</emphasis>
–methylsekikaic acids.
</paragraph>
