</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="61" pageNumber="62" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="61.[136,1452,1274,1841]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,298,1598,1624]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Remarks</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="V. Marcano &amp; A. Morales" authorityYear="2021" box="[315,537,1598,1624]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Ramalinaceae" genus="Ramalina" kingdom="Fungi" order="Lecanorales" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="tenaensis">
<emphasis box="[315,537,1598,1624]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Ramalina tenaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by its strongly contorted branches with verruculose surface, its lack of soralia and pseudocyphellae and its uni-septate, short ellipsoid spores (8–10 x 4–4.5 µm). This species is very similar to 
<emphasis box="[255,524,1670,1696]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. H. Howe" authorityYear="1914" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeous" baseAuthorityYear="1767" box="[255,356,1671,1696]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Ramalinaceae" genus="Ramalina" kingdom="Fungi" order="Lecanorales" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="usnea">R. usnea</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[370,524,1670,1696]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Ramalinaceae" genus="Ramalina" kingdom="Fungi" order="Lecanorales" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="bogotensis">R. bogotensis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bertero ex Nylander" authorityYear="1870" box="[583,715,1670,1696]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Ramalinaceae" genus="Ramalina" kingdom="Fungi" order="Lecanorales" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="chilensis">
<emphasis box="[583,715,1670,1696]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">R. chilensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
–all with contorted branches– but it is distinguished from them by the shape and size of its spores and its verruculose surface. The other three species show long fusiform spores and branches with a smooth surface. Chemically 
<taxonomicName authorityName="V. Marcano &amp; A. Morales" authorityYear="2021" box="[695,831,1743,1768]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Ramalinaceae" genus="Ramalina" kingdom="Fungi" order="Lecanorales" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="tenaensis">
<emphasis box="[695,831,1743,1768]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">R. tenaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. H. Howe" authorityYear="1914" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeous" baseAuthorityYear="1767" box="[1040,1137,1743,1768]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Ramalinaceae" genus="Ramalina" kingdom="Fungi" order="Lecanorales" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="usnea">
<emphasis box="[1040,1137,1743,1768]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">R. usnea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the latter species lacks 2ˊ– 
<emphasis box="[173,193,1779,1805]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">O</emphasis>
–methylsekikaic acid while boninic acid occurs in only one chemical strain of this species (see below).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="61.[136,1452,1274,1841]" box="[189,753,1814,1841]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
The name of the species refers to the 
<typeStatus box="[608,656,1815,1841]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
